Harvard students are taking a class on rest habits.
This year, a new course at Harvard University allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing culture of caffeine-fueled, all-night study.
One scholar observed that students at the world's top universities are often confused about the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
