Bernard Vann: Celebration of the Clergy of the Cross Victory of the First World War
The only Church of England clergyman to win a Victoria Cross during the First World War as a combatant has been honoured in his home town 100 years later.
Lieutenant-Colonel and Reverend Bernard Vann was awarded the medal on 29 September 1918 for the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was shot down by a sniper four days later and never knew he had won Britain's highest military honour.
His two grandchildren unveiled a memorial tombstone at a parade on Saturday in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "magnificently symbolic" that the tombstone was presented exactly 100 years after his grandfather's awarded feat.
According to The London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a very thick fog and under intense cannon and machine gun fire".
Later he ran towards the line of fire and, with "maximum courage" he made the line advance before throwing himself on a cannon with one hand and leaving three members of the detachment stunned.
The lieutenant colonel was shot down by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just a month before the war ended.
Michael Vann (72) said that his grandfather's actions were a feat he could never match, which makes you feel humbled.
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also left a wreath after the parade, conducted by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was very honored to be part of the parade and added that the value of a true hero is shown by the support he will receive from many people.
