Germany's new warship, postponed again
The new German Navy frigate was supposed to have been completed in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but will not do so until at least next year due to faulty systems and an increase in cost, according to local media.
The completion of Rheinland-Pfalz, the lead ship of the new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship was supposed to have joined the Navy in 2014, but problems after construction have marked the end of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the former Bremen-class frigates.
It is believed to include a powerful cannon, an array of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as technology against stealth actions, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other outstanding features include longer periods between maintenance: it should be possible to use the new frigates for up to two years without passing through national ports.
However, these continuous delays imply that the forward-thinking ships, which were predicted to project Germany as a powerful force abroad, will already be obsolete when they enter service, according to Die Zeit.
The ill-fated F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy rejected the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the builder once delivered.
Little is known of the reasons for the return, but German media have cited several "material and technical defects" of the ship that made it unusable if used in combat missions.
The technical problems are significant, as approximately 120 sailors, half the crew required for the former Bremen-class frigates, operate on Baden-Württemberg-class ships.
In addition, the ship's weight has also been found to be excessive, which reduces performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future improvements.
It is believed that the Rheinland-Pfalz, of 7,000 tons, will weigh twice as much as similar class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Apart from the faulty materials, the cost of the project, which includes the training of the crew, is also starting to pose a problem.
It is believed to have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from an initial budget of 2.2 billion euros.
The problems of the new frigates have become a matter of special importance, if one takes into account recent warnings that indicate that Germany's naval military power is weakening.
This year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, has acknowledged that the navy  is running out of ships that can be used.
The official said the situation has worsened over time because the old ships were taken out of service, but no new ones were provided as replacements.
She has regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg class frigates could join the Navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
A new study on a farm in the Scottish Highlands aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed.
It is hoped that the discoveries may provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, as well as northern and water-eared bats at Inverewe Botanic Gardens, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to track bat activity during the season.
Volunteers and staff from the UK National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with handheld detectors.
Experts' sound analysis of the recordings will determine the sound frequency of the bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and habitat map will be created to create a detailed landscape-scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the National Trust for Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Building and restoration work threatens bats, as it affects nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do paper-based mosquito nets and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bat people are not actually blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-location technique to locate insects and obstacles that interfere with their flight.
The National Trust for Scotland, which is responsible for over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with proper training, who conduct surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues on a regular basis.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve at Threave Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The estate's administrator, David Thompson, claims that it is the ideal territory for the species.
"Here in Threave, we have a large bat area", he says.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all good habitat.
But we still don't know many aspects of bats, so the work we're doing here and at other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.
It stresses the importance of checking for bats before doing maintenance work on property, as the possible unintentional destruction of a single maternity nest could kill more than 400 females and young, potentially wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, attack, harass and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an official with the Scottish Bat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to step up and help.
He stated: 'We still have a lot to learn from bats and, in the case of some of our species, we do not have enough data on their population.'
